rviews with more than 200 white and minority local leaders, and through analysis of local education and public safety policies, he finds that unconventional channels, namely neighborhood groups and community-based organizations, strongly influence the representation of minority interests.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxSuffrage. 0aHispanic AmericansxSuffrage. 0aLocal governmentzUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aProportional representationzUnited States. 0aRepresentative government and representationzUnited States. 0aSociology, UrbanzUnited States. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791482261423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791482261/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles